    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** - May 26, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🪓 ClickUp made the layoff deck sentient\n\nThe AI productivity revolution has reached its inevitable HR milestone: fewer people, more dashboards, and a memo wearing a lab coat.\n\n- **The cut:** ClickUp CEO Zeb Evans said the company laid off 22% of staff after being valued at $4 billion in 2021.\n- **The pitch:** Evans framed it as an AI-native shift, not cost-cutting, while promising million-dollar salary bands for workers who create outsized impact with AI.\n- **The machinery:** ClickUp has rolled out roughly 3,000 internal AI agents, with employees expected to direct the systems and review their output.\n\n*Apparently the future of work comes with a severance package and a prompt window.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/25/what-clickups-mass-layoff-tells-us-about-the-future-of-work/)\n\n---\n\n## 🔐 Google keys forgot how doors work\n\nAI security now includes the charming possibility that deleting a key means asking it politely to stop sometime before lunch.\n\n- **The window:** Aikido researchers found deleted Google API keys could keep authenticating for up to 23 minutes; the median revocation lag was about 16 minutes.\n- **The bill:** TechCrunch tied the issue to Gemini-related abuse, including developers hit with five-figure charges after old Maps-style keys became usable for AI calls.\n- **The answer:** Google refunded some reported victims, but The Register says the company treated the delay as intended behavior rather than a fixable security flaw.\n\n*Machine-speed defense is great. Machine-speed billing remains undefeated.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/24/everyone-is-navigating-ai-security-in-real-time-even-google/) | [The Register](https://www.theregister.com/devops/2026/05/21/threat-hunters-find-google-api-keys-still-usable-23-minutes-after-deletion/5244504)\n\n---\n\n## ⛪ The Vatican found the model card\n\nPope Leo XIV has entered the AI policy chat, which is awkward for everyone still pretending this is just a feature rollout.\n\n- **The document:** Leo published his first encyclical, Magnifica Humanitas, on May 25, focused on safeguarding people in the age of artificial intelligence.\n- **The target:** The 200-page text warns that concentrated technical power can become opaque, escape public oversight, and deepen dependency, exclusion and manipulation.\n- **The demand:** Leo called for clear oversight, community participation, and an end to the AI arms race for geopolitical or commercial dominance.\n\n*Silicon Valley wanted spiritual alignment. It got procurement notes from Rome.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/25/the-popes-ai-encyclical-isnt-really-about-ai/) | [Vatican](https://www.vatican.va/)\n\n---\n\n## 🎙️ Amazon put a stenographer on your wrist\n\nThe AI wearable dream remains alive, mostly because nobody has successfully killed the fantasy of a tiny assistant recording your day.\n\n- **The gadget:** Bee, the wrist device Amazon acquired last year, records conversations, transcribes them, and produces summaries through a companion app.\n- **The promise:** TechCrunch found it useful for consented work calls, where it can break down a meeting without forcing the user to replay the whole thing.\n- **The tax:** Bee asks for broad permissions, including location, photos, contacts, calendar and notifications, while storing accumulated data in the cloud.\n\n*As ever, the assistant is helpful. The part where it remembers your entire life is the invoice.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/05/24/i-tried-amazons-bee-wearable-and-am-both-intrigued-and-slightly-creeped-out/) | [Amazon](https://www.aboutamazon.com/)"
  }
]
